      <h2>Translation Requirements in UAE</h2>
      <p>After completing the Indian attestation chain, you need Arabic translation in UAE. Translation happens AFTER attestation, not before.</p>

      <h3>When MOJ Translation is Required</h3>
      <p>Any document submitted to a UAE government entity needs MOJ-certified legal translation. This includes MOHRE, GDRFA, MOHESR, DHA, KHDA, and MOFA. The MOJ seal confirms the translation is from a licensed translator recognized by UAE courts.</p>

      <p>Private employers may accept <a href="/resources/moj-vs-certified/">certified translation</a> for internal HR records. However, the MOHRE work permit application requires MOJ translation. To avoid paying twice, get MOJ translation from the start.</p>

      <h3>What the Translator Translates</h3>
      <p>The MOJ translator translates your entire degree certificate including university seal, signatures, degree title, major, grades, and issue date. The translation also includes notation of all attestation stamps: university registrar, HRD, and MEA apostille.</p>

      <p>The final document is your original degree with translation attached and the MOJ seal. MOHRE, MOHESR, and GDRFA accept this combined document.</p>

      <h3>Name Transliteration</h3>
      <p>Indian names often have multiple English transliterations. Suresh Kumar might become سوريش كومار or سريش قمار depending on the translator. This causes problems if the Arabic spelling doesn't match other translated documents.</p>

      <div class="warning-note">
        <i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i>
        <div>
          <strong>Critical Name Matching Rule:</strong> Before translation, provide your passport copy to the translator. Insist they use the exact Arabic spelling from your UAE visa or Emirates ID. If this is your first UAE document, confirm the spelling matches your <a href="/personal/vital-records/birth/">birth certificate translation</a> if you have one.
        </div>
      </div>

